<HEADLINE>
SINGAPORE WELCOMES TAIWAN INVESTORS: SINGAPORE PM
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Singapore,  March  15 (CNA) 03/15/07  18:57:58 (By Charles Kang
and Deborah Kuo)
</P>
<P>
Singapore Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong said Thursday that
Taiwan companies are welcome to invest in Singapore and that he
hopes bilateral economic and trade relations will become closer.
</P>
<P>
Lee, who doubles as minister for finance of the city state, made
the remarks during a brief talk with Republic of China
Representative to Singapore Hu Wei- jen at a cocktail party
sponsored by the Singapore Chinese Chamber of Commerce and
Industry (SCCCI) to mark the inauguration of the chamber's new
board of directors.
</P>
<P>
Hu told Lee that bilateral economic, cultural and educational
exchanges between Taiwan and Singapore have become much closer in
recent years and that a major group representing Taiwan's
business and industrial sectors is scheduled to visit Singapore
in April to further cement ties in that regard.
</P>
<P>
Hu said that as Taiwan's representative in Singapore, he has been
encouraging Taiwan businessmen and investors to relocate some of
their investments to the city state to take advantage of its
fully-transparent  trade regulations and commendable  investment
climate and environment.
</P>
<P>
One of the most important business centers in Asia, Singapore can
also serve as a gateway for Taiwan investors seeking other
markets in Southeast Asia and the Middle East, Hu said.
</P>
